<div id="review_3894340793" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3894340793" />
    <a title="Glenn Sumi" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/28854579-glenn-sumi"><img alt="Glenn Sumi" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1444333567p2/28854579.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3894340793?book_show_action=true">Mar 28, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Glenn Sumi" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Glenn Sumi" href="/user/show/28854579-glenn-sumi">Glenn Sumi</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780007815531" href="/book/show/1009709.Death_on_the_Nile">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3894340793" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8331955122212372841">I&apos;ve been in a bit of a reading slump for much of 2021. Work, stress, catching up on Oscar movies, a deadly pandemic... ya know, the usual distractions.<br/><br/>But a couple of weeks ago, as I was watching the disturbing (and excellent) documentary Allen V. Farrow, Mia Farrow mentioned in an offhand way making this picture in the late 70s, an adaptation of the Agatha Christie mystery. I had heard of it, of course, but never seen it. Then I saw the e-Book pop up in my library app.<br/><br/>And wouldn&apos;t you know? A </span>
  <span id="freeText8331955122212372841" style="display:none">I've been in a bit of a reading slump for much of 2021. Work, stress, catching up on Oscar movies, a deadly pandemic... ya know, the usual distractions.<br /><br />But a couple of weeks ago, as I was watching the disturbing (and excellent) documentary Allen V. Farrow, Mia Farrow mentioned in an offhand way making this picture in the late 70s, an adaptation of the Agatha Christie mystery. I had heard of it, of course, but never seen it. Then I saw the e-Book pop up in my library app.<br /><br />And wouldn't you know? A murder mystery was exactly what I needed to read at this time. <br /><br />Now, I'm not the biggest mystery fan. As far as genre goes, I prefer hard-boiled crime fiction, thrillers, horror and suspense. But there's something very satisfying about a book where you're given a corpse, clues and many suspects and YOU HAVE TO FIGURE OUT WHO DID THE DEED. <br /><br />Yes, during a time of great uncertainty, it was wonderful having things wrapped up in the final chapters. <br /><br />At first I was put off by all the characters involved in this story about a wealthy, beautiful young British heiress who's on her honeymoon and is killed on a luxury ship on the Nile. At one point, I even thought of making up a chart of everyone's names and motives. Then I thought that was silly and too much like work and that I should just enjoy the book. If Christie is as good as people say she is (this is only my second or third of her novels), she'll lead me along capably.<br /><br />And she did. I'd read a few chapters a night, usually in bed. I enjoyed the exotic (to me, anyway) setting and the chance to travel and sightsee when most of the world can’t. Some of Christie's characters were very amusing, especially a snobbish old biddy. And I liked spending time with the odd little Belgian detective, Hercule Poirot, and his vanity, perceptiveness and French expressions.<br /><br />I bookmarked a few passages as being OF POSSIBLE SIGNIFICANCE. I had my prime suspects in mind. And Dame Agatha planted some very amusing red herrings along the way. The final part of the book was truly page-turning, where characters would basically say, “So X didn’t do it, but then who did?” at the end of each chapter. <br /><br />So this was great fun. I'm looking forward to seeing both the 70s adaptation and a new one, which was supposed to open theatrically this year but has been pushed to February 2022. And I'm keen to read another Poirot mystery soon. I know there are dozens of books out there.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8331955122212372841" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


