    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2342488611" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2342488611" />
    <a title="Dennis" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/64621419-dennis"><img alt="Dennis" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1627066387p2/64621419.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2342488611?book_show_action=true">Apr 02, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Dennis" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Dennis" href="/user/show/64621419-dennis">Dennis</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/38194295-death-on-the-nile">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/64621419-dennis?shelf=mystery">mystery</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2342488611" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16574398430313877457">Only my second Poirot, and I might have to rethink how I&apos;m choosing the ones I want to read. Which is to say, I shouldn&apos;t care that much about the setting, because Christie apparently did not do so either. It&apos;s really pretty much only about the case.<br/><br/>And the case, again, was great fun. The buildup however, because &quot;case&quot; of course also includes the characters and their relationships and motivations, the buildup took a bit too long for my liking. But when the crime had finally happened and Poirot </span>
  <span id="freeText16574398430313877457" style="display:none">Only my second Poirot, and I might have to rethink how I'm choosing the ones I want to read. Which is to say, I shouldn't care that much about the setting, because Christie apparently did not do so either. It's really pretty much only about the case.<br /><br />And the case, again, was great fun. The buildup however, because "case" of course also includes the characters and their relationships and motivations, the buildup took a bit too long for my liking. But when the crime had finally happened and Poirot got to work, it was again a real page-turner. Which is even more incredible, when one considers that very early on already I was pretty sure who had done it, and also why. Even before the whole thing had actually happened, in fact. The only question that remained for me was the how. So, was the culprit too obvious? Hm, possibly, yes. But it might also just have been luck. There was one particular clue that tipped me off and made everything fall into place for me immediately. But there are certainly enough other clues that could have lead me on a completely different path.<br /><br />In any case, I prefered the denouement in this one over that in <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/853510.Murder_on_the_Orient_Express__Hercule_Poirot___10_" title="Murder on the Orient Express (Hercule Poirot, #10) by Agatha Christie" rel="nofollow noopener"> Murder on the Orient Express</a>, because it actually made sense. Whereas in the other novel I thought it was just humbug. Overall though, I still liked my first Poirot better. <i>Murder on the Orient Express</i> is a more tightly structured novel than <i>Death on the Nile</i>. That, and of course not already being almost certain about the who and why, made the investigation just that bit more fun. Even if the ending was disappointing.<br /><br />Ultimately this one's a <b>3.5</b> for me again. Even though I liked it less than my first Poirot, I'm once again rounding up. Both books are just too entertaining to only give them three stars.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16574398430313877457" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


