  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2826224682" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2826224682" />
    <a title="Laysee" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4863523-laysee"><img alt="Laysee" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1459741824p2/4863523.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2826224682?book_show_action=true">May 19, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Laysee" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Laysee" href="/user/show/4863523-laysee">Laysee</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2826224682" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3948507714817096187">Dame Agatha Christie was an inimitable detective fiction writer and I, the non-mystery reader, was astounded by her gift for telling a thoroughly absorbing story. I finally met Hercule Poirot, her famous Belgian detective, and was equally impressed by this little man with the curly moustache and an extraordinary capacity for observation and problem-solving. I needed a palette cleanser from a couple of dark chocolaty books I was reading, and so I took a cruise on the Karnak to Egypt. On board was</span>
  <span id="freeText3948507714817096187" style="display:none">Dame Agatha Christie was an inimitable detective fiction writer and I, the non-mystery reader, was astounded by her gift for telling a thoroughly absorbing story. I finally met Hercule Poirot, her famous Belgian detective, and was equally impressed by this little man with the curly moustache and an extraordinary capacity for observation and problem-solving. I needed a palette cleanser from a couple of dark chocolaty books I was reading, and so I took a cruise on the Karnak to Egypt. On board was Poirot in his silk suit who was on vacation, except of course, Dame Christie made sure there was no rest for the wickedly brilliant. And then, there was no rest for me either. Forty percent into this novel, a death occurred, and I became the amateur sleuth and I realized, not a very good one.<br /><br />Chapter 1 opens with a gathering of the troop for the trip down the Nile. There is Linnet Ridgeway, a radiant and assured 20-year-old heiress who has <i>‘the combined effect of money and charm.’</i> A society beauty can hardly escape envy and hatred from some quarters. But Linnet is loved by her best friend, Jacqueline (Jackie) de Bellefort, a penurious but fiercely intelligent girl who does not begrudge hard work, and who is now happily engaged to an equally impoverished and handsome young man, Simon Doyle. Jackie and Simon make plans to marry and honeymoon in Egypt, but Simon needs a job, which Jackie hopes Linnet can offer. Linnet offers much more. She marries Simon! Jackie is eaten with bitterness and stalks the newly-wed couple on their honeymoon down the Nile. The trio aside, there is Mrs Salome Otterbourne, a struggling romance writer and her beautiful but sulky daughter, Rosalie, who is insanely jealous of Linnet being <i>‘so horribly successful and poised and assured.’</i> There is Linnet’s maid, Louise, who is at her beck and call but knows how to line her own pockets. There is Andrew Pennington, Linnet’s uncle and American trustee, who is shocked at the sudden news of her marriage, which has implications for her fortune and his, too. There is Tim Allerton who accompanies his mother, but unlike Rosalie, has an easier task with parenting an aged parent. Tim is unaccountably hostile to Poirot. There is Cornelia Robson, a humble girl from NY, who is grateful for a chance of a lifetime to accompany her pompous and socially well connected cousin, Marie van Schuyler, to Egypt. In tow is Miss Bower, van Schuyler’s businesslike hospital nurse. Others include Dr. Bessner (a German doctor); Ferguson, a disgruntled socialist who finds Egypt vulgar; Jim Fanthrop, a lawyer; Signor Guido Richetti, an Italian trouble maker. Each of these folks has his or her own secret flaws, and when three deaths happen in quick succession, no one is beyond suspicion. Poirot is joined by Colonel Race to investigate this nasty turn of events.<br /><br />The most satisfying aspect of reading a story like this is following the mind of Monsieur Hercule Poirot. He has a good understanding of human behavior and astounding powers of observation and perception. He has a phenomenal memory for faces and voices. He also has good counsel for unhappy characters on board ship, counsel that is unfortunately not heeded. It is most gratifying to witness Poirot’s smugness when he is at work: <i>‘Because I am Hercule Poirot. I do not need to be told...’</i><br /><br />True to her reputation, Dame Christie has written an air tight and a totally plausible detective story. What I did not expect are a couple of observations that carry a grain of truth: (a) <i>’It is dangerous to love someone ‘beyond reason and beyond rectitude and beyond pity.’</i> (b) <i>’Don’t open your heart to evil. Because—if you do—evil will come…Yes, very surely evil will come…It will enter in and make its home within you, and after a little while it will no longer be possible to drive it out.’</i> One of the characters found out too late: <i>‘It’s so dreadfully easy - killing people. And you begin to feel that it doesn’t matter... that it’s only you that matters. It’s dangerous - that.”</i><br /><br /><b>Death on the Nile</b> is a tantalizing detective story. I enjoyed my first meeting with Monsieur Poirot and look forward again to watching his brilliant mind at work.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3948507714817096187" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

